{"descriptions":[{"id":337,"title":null,"content":"\u003cp\u003eExamples: ཨ་རོ་, ཨ་ཆུ་, [རེད་]ད་\u003c/p\u003e","source_url":null,"is_primary":false,"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:33 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:33 UTC","authors":[{"id":"2","fullname":"David Germano"}]},{"id":338,"title":null,"content":"\u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eExpressive particles are common in both Standard and Literary Tibetan. Some go at the beginning of a sentence and some at the end, after the verb.\u003c/p\u003e \u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eOf those that go at the beginning, the most common are:\u003c/p\u003e \u003cul\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཨོ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Oh!\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཨ་ལའི་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Well, well....\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཨ་ཙི་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Rats!\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;Darn!\u0026rdquo; \u0026ldquo;Bugger!\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཨ་རོ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Ow!\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཨ་ཆུ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Oh, that\u0026rsquo;s cold!\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཨ་ཚ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Ouch, that\u0026rsquo;s hot!\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཨ་ཁ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;What a shame!\u0026rdquo; \u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཨ་མ་\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Oh Lordy!\u0026rdquo; (Literally: \u0026ldquo;O mother!\u0026rdquo;)\u003c/li\u003e \u003c/ul\u003e \u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003eThe particles that appear most frequently at the end of a sentence are:\u003c/p\u003e \u003cul\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eད་ \u003c/span\u003e\u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཔ་\u003c/span\u003e (and its variants \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eག་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eང་\u003c/span\u003e)\u003c/li\u003e \u003c/ul\u003e \u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eད་\u003c/span\u003e often implies that the speaker is not in agreement with the person to whom he\u0026rsquo;s speaking, or is emphasizing the surprising or threatening nature of the situation in question.\u003c/p\u003e \u003cul\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eའདི་དཔེ་རང་རེད་ད།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;It\u0026rsquo;s pretty amazing, huh?\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eརྐུ་མ་ཤོར་གྱི་རེད་ད།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;But you\u0026rsquo;ll be robbed!\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཉེན་ཁ་ཡོད་རེད་ད།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;But there is some danger!\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eརྟ་ཤོར་སོང་ད།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;Watch out, the horse has escaped!\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003c/ul\u003e \u003cp class=\"Paragraph\"\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཔ་\u003c/span\u003e and its variants \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eག་\u003c/span\u003e and \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eང་\u003c/span\u003e are subject to the same modifications as the interrogative particles \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཔས་\u003c/span\u003e, \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eགས་\u003c/span\u003e, and \u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eངས་\u003c/span\u003e (xxlink 2.3.1). Using these implies that that speaker is trying to elicit agreement with what he is saying, and correspond to tag questions. They may therefore be translated in English by \u0026ldquo;Isn\u0026rsquo;t that so?\u0026rdquo; or \u0026ldquo;Don\u0026rsquo;t you think?\u0026rdquo; English might also convey these by intonation.\u003c/p\u003e \u003cul\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཁྱེད་རང་གི་སྤུ་གུ་ཆེན་པོ་ཆགས་འདུག་ག\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;My God, how your child has grown!\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eད་ལྟ་ཕྱི་པོ་རེད་པ།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;It\u0026rsquo;s late now, isn\u0026rsquo;t it?\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eསྐྱིད་པོ་བྱུང་སོང་ང་།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;It was very pleasant! Eh?\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eངས་ཁྱེད་རང་ལ་ཞུས་བྱུང་ང་།\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;I told you, didn\u0026rsquo;t I?\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003cli\u003e\u003cspan class=\"tibetan\" title=\"Type ID here\"\u003eཁྱེད་རང་སློབ་སྦྱོང་ཧུར་བརྩོན་ཞེ་དྲགས་བྱེད་ཀྱི་འདུག་ག\u003c/span\u003e \u0026ldquo;You study really hard, don\u0026rsquo;t you?\u0026rdquo;\u003c/li\u003e \u003c/ul\u003e","source_url":null,"is_primary":true,"created_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:33 UTC","updated_at":"2013-09-15 04:07:33 UTC","authors":[{"id":"6","fullname":"Nicolas Tournadre"}]}]}